  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Creating Wealth in the Democratic Republic of Congo</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project will benefit 21,924 indirect beneficiaries (4 family members per loan client and 0.2 employees per loan client). As a result of more sustainable livelihoods and wealth creation, dependants of clients will have increased access to better nutrition and education, as well as improved housing and health care. Family members will also benefit from increased client self-esteem as well as leadership and communication skills. Entire communities will benefit as the local economy is stimulated through increasingly productive businesses and economic diversification.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project will reduce poverty and inequality in Kinshasa by increasing the availability of financial services and training to previously excluded populations in the informal sector, particularly women (65% of direct beneficiaries). This will contribute to the achievement of MDG1 and MDG3 in the DRC by creating wealth, building household assets, and reducing vulnerability to shocks. Target beneficiaries will be empowered to participate in income-generating activities and work their way out of poverty through their own efforts.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will create wealth and reduce poverty in the DRC through improving the livelihoods of informal sector workers in Kinshasa. Access to micro-credit and training will increase household incomes; 6,264 jobs will be created or sustained; access to safe savings facilities will enable poor people in Kinshasa to build assets, reduce vulnerability and smooth consumption. An estimated 20,880 family members will indirectly benefit from better nutrition, health and education.</narrative>
  </description>
